    location: "Jerusalem", dateline: "The Royal Palace",
    headline: "Prophet Tells David a Story About a Stolen Lamb — David Condemns the Man, Then Learns He Is the Man",
    summary: "After David's murder of Uriah and taking of Bathsheba, the prophet Nathan came with a parable. David gave judgment against the man in the story — then Nathan said: you are the man.",
    ref: "2 Samuel 12:1-12",
    anchorVerse: { verse: "12:7", text: "Then Nathan said to David: you are the man! This is what the LORD, the God of Israel, says: I anointed you king over Israel, and I delivered you from the hand of Saul." },
    body: [
      "The LORD sent Nathan to David. Nathan told him: there were two men in a certain town, one rich and one poor. The rich man had a very large number of sheep and cattle, but the poor man had nothing except one little ewe lamb he had bought. He raised it, and it grew up with him and his children. It shared his food, drank from his cup, and even slept in his arms. It was like a daughter to him.",
      "Now a traveler came to the rich man, but the rich man refrained from taking one of his own sheep or cattle to prepare a meal for the traveler who had come to him. Instead, he took the ewe lamb that belonged to the poor man and prepared it for the one who had come to him.",
      "David burned with anger against the man and said to Nathan: as surely as the LORD lives, the man who did this must die. He must pay for that lamb four times over, because he did such a thing and had no pity. Then Nathan said: you are the man.",
      "He declared the LORD's word to David: I anointed you king over Israel and I delivered you from the hand of Saul. I gave your master's house to you, and your master's wives into your arms. I gave you all Israel and Judah. Why did you despise the word of the LORD by doing what is evil in his eyes? You struck down Uriah the Hittite with the sword and took his wife to be your own. Now, therefore, the sword will never depart from your house. David said to Nathan: I have sinned against the LORD. Nathan replied: the LORD has taken away your sin. You are not going to die. But because by doing this you have shown utter contempt for the LORD, the son born to you will die.",
    ],
    scripture: [
      { verse: "12:1-3", text: "The LORD sent Nathan to David. When he came to him, he said: there were two men in a certain town, one rich and one poor. The poor man had nothing except one little ewe lamb." },
      { verse: "12:5-6", text: "David burned with anger against the man and said to Nathan: as surely as the LORD lives, the man who did this must die! He must pay for that lamb four times over." },
      { verse: "12:7", text: "Then Nathan said to David: you are the man!" },
      { verse: "12:13", text: "Then David said to Nathan: I have sinned against the LORD. Nathan replied: the LORD has taken away your sin. You are not going to die." },
    ],
    commentary: [
      { author: "Matthew Henry", era: "1706", text: "Nathan's parable was a masterpiece of pastoral wisdom — it brought David to judge himself before he knew it. The man who would not see his own sin was made to see it in another's story." },
      { author: "John Gill", era: "1763", text: "David's swift and severe judgment — the man must die — showed his conscience was not yet awakened to his own case. When Nathan turned the mirror, the shock was total." },
      { author: "Charles Spurgeon", era: "1880", text: "You are the man — four of the most devastating words in Scripture. No lengthy argument. Just identification. Nathan's courage in saying them was as remarkable as David's sin in earning them." },
      { author: "John Nelson Darby", era: "1857", text: "The LORD sent Nathan — he did not abandon David to his sin. Rebuke is an act of love. The word of God is used to heal before it is used to judge." },
      { author: "Adam Clarke", era: "1831", text: "David's immediate confession — I have sinned against the LORD — was the difference between him and Saul. Both sinned; both were confronted. One confessed without qualification; the other made excuses." },
    ],
