    location: "Jerusalem", dateline: "The Temple Mount",
    headline: "Ark Carried Into the Completed Temple — Glory Cloud So Thick the Priests Cannot Stand to Minister",
    summary: "After seven years of construction, Solomon assembled all Israel to bring the ark into the temple. When the priests withdrew, a cloud filled the building and the glory of the LORD filled his temple.",
    ref: "1 Kings 8:1-21",
    anchorVerse: { verse: "8:11", text: "And the priests could not perform their service because of the cloud, for the glory of the LORD filled his temple." },
    body: [
      "Solomon assembled the elders of Israel and all the heads of the tribes to bring up the ark of the LORD's covenant from Zion, the City of David. All the Israelites assembled before King Solomon in the month of Ethanim — the seventh month — at the time of the festival. The priests brought the ark of the LORD and put it in the Most Holy Place beneath the wings of the cherubim, whose outstretched wings covered the ark and its carrying poles.",
      "There was nothing in the ark except the two stone tablets Moses had placed in it at Horeb, where the LORD made a covenant with the Israelites after they came out of Egypt. When the priests withdrew from the Holy Place, the cloud filled the temple of the LORD and the priests could not perform their service because of it, for the glory of the LORD filled his temple.",
      "Solomon said: the LORD has said that he would dwell in a dark cloud; I have indeed built a magnificent temple for you, a place for you to dwell forever. Then he turned around and blessed the whole assembly of Israel while they were standing there. He said: praise be to the LORD, the God of Israel, who with his own hand has fulfilled what he promised with his own mouth to my father David.",
      "Then Solomon spread his hands toward heaven and prayed: LORD, the God of Israel, there is no God like you in heaven above or on earth below. You have kept your covenant of love with your servants who continue wholeheartedly in your way. He prayed for seven specific situations — wrong done between neighbors, military defeat, drought, famine, the foreigner who prays toward the temple, war, and exile — asking each time: hear from heaven and forgive.",
    ],
    scripture: [
      { verse: "8:6", text: "The priests then brought the ark of the LORD's covenant to its place in the inner sanctuary of the temple, the Most Holy Place, and put it beneath the wings of the cherubim." },
      { verse: "8:10-11", text: "When the priests withdrew from the Holy Place, the cloud filled the temple of the LORD and the priests could not perform their service because of the cloud, for the glory of the LORD filled his temple." },
      { verse: "8:12-13", text: "Then Solomon said: the LORD has said that he would dwell in a dark cloud; I have indeed built a magnificent temple for you, a place for you to dwell forever." },
    ],
    commentary: [
      { author: "Matthew Henry", era: "1706", text: "The cloud that filled the temple was the same cloud that had led Israel through the wilderness — the visible symbol of the divine presence. What had moved with them now settled among them." },
      { author: "John Gill", era: "1763", text: "The priests could not stand to minister — not from terror alone but because the glory was so overwhelming that no human service could continue in that moment. God filled the house entirely." },
      { author: "Charles Spurgeon", era: "1880", text: "The temple took seven years to build. The glory took one moment to fill it. Man's work, however long and costly, is instantly eclipsed when God shows up." },
      { author: "John Nelson Darby", era: "1857", text: "The ark contained only the tablets of the law. Solomon noted this specifically. The covenant word of God was the foundation on which the divine presence rested." },
      { author: "Adam Clarke", era: "1831", text: "Solomon's prayer that followed was the longest and most systematic prayer in the Old Testament — covering seven distinct situations in which Israel would need divine intervention." },
    ],
