      `Jacob lived in Canaan. His son Joseph, seventeen years old, tended flocks with his brothers and brought a bad report about them to their father. Jacob loved Joseph more than any of his other sons — he was the son of his old age — and made him an ornate robe. When his brothers saw their father's favoritism, they hated Joseph and could not speak a kind word to him.`,
      `Joseph had two dreams. In the first, his brothers' sheaves gathered around his and bowed down to it. In the second, the sun, moon, and eleven stars bowed down to him. His father rebuked him but kept the matter in mind. His brothers were jealous.`,
      `When Joseph's brothers had gone to graze their father's flocks near Shechem, Jacob sent Joseph to check on them. The brothers saw him coming in the distance and plotted to kill him. Reuben suggested they throw him into a cistern instead, planning to rescue him later. When Joseph reached them, they stripped off his robe and threw him in.`,
      `A caravan of Ishmaelite traders passed by heading to Egypt. Judah suggested selling Joseph rather than killing him. They sold him for twenty shekels of silver. The traders took him to Egypt. Reuben returned to the cistern, found it empty, and tore his clothes. The brothers dipped Joseph's robe in goat's blood and took it to Jacob. He concluded a wild animal had torn his son apart. Jacob mourned many days and refused to be comforted.`
