      `The LORD gave Moses and Aaron detailed instructions. On the tenth day of the first month, each household was to select a year-old male lamb without defect. On the fourteenth day they were to slaughter it at twilight. They were to take some of the blood and put it on the sides and tops of the doorframes of the houses where they ate the lamb. They were to eat the meat roasted over fire, with bitter herbs and unleavened bread. They were to eat it in haste, with cloaks tucked in, sandals on their feet, and staff in hand. It was the LORD's Passover.`,
      `On that same night God would pass through Egypt and strike down every firstborn — both people and animals. When he saw the blood on the doorframe, he would pass over that doorway. The blood would be a sign — when I see the blood, I will pass over you.`,
      `At midnight the LORD struck down all the firstborn in Egypt. There was not a house without someone dead. Pharaoh and all his officials and all the Egyptians got up during the night. There was loud wailing in Egypt.`,
      `During the night Pharaoh summoned Moses and Aaron: get out. Take your flocks and herds. Go. The Egyptians urged the people to hurry and leave before they all died. The Israelites took their dough before yeast had been added, carried it on their shoulders, and asked the Egyptians for articles of silver, gold, and clothing. The Egyptians gave them what they asked for and they plundered Egypt.`,
      `There were about six hundred thousand men on foot, plus women and children. They left Rameses for Succoth. They baked unleavened bread with the dough they had brought from Egypt. They had been driven out without time to prepare food.`
