      `The LORD gave Moses and Aaron a new law: the Israelites were to bring a red heifer without defect or blemish, one that had never been under a yoke. It was to be given to the priest Eleazar, taken outside the camp, and slaughtered in front of him. Eleazar was to sprinkle some of its blood toward the front of the tent of meeting seven times. The heifer was to be burned completely — hide, flesh, blood, and dung. The priest was then to take cedar wood, hyssop, and scarlet wool and throw them onto the burning heifer. After this, both the priest and the man who burned it were unclean until evening.`,
      `A man who was clean was to gather the ashes and put them in a ceremonially clean place outside the camp where they were to be kept. They were to be used for the water of cleansing — for purification from sin.`,
      `Whenever someone died in a tent, everyone who entered and everything in the tent was unclean for seven days. Anyone who touched a body in the open field — or a bone or grave — was also unclean for seven days. For cleansing, the ashes were to be taken and mixed with fresh water in a jar. A man who was clean was to dip a hyssop branch in the water and sprinkle it on the tent, the furnishings, all the people present, and anyone who had touched a bone, body, or grave. On the third day and on the seventh day the cleansing water was sprinkled. On the seventh day, they were to wash their clothes and bathe, and they would be clean by evening.`,
      `*The old generation dies; a new generation prepares to enter the land*`
