      `After Abimelek had governed Israel three years, God stirred up animosity between him and the citizens of Shechem, who acted treacherously against him. This happened so that the crime against Jerub-Baal's seventy sons would be avenged. The citizens of Shechem set men on the hilltops to ambush and rob everyone who passed by. Gaal son of Ebed and his brothers moved into Shechem and stirred up the inhabitants against Abimelek.`,
      `When Abimelek heard what Gaal had said, he and his forces attacked Shechem. He drove Gaal out, then returned the next day and stationed his men in two groups in the fields. When the people came out of the city, he cut them down. He captured the city and killed the people in it and demolished it and scattered salt over it.`,
      `When the thousand men and women who occupied the Tower of Shechem heard about this, they entered the stronghold of the temple of El-Berith. Abimelek went up Mount Zalmon and cut branches and put them on his shoulders. He instructed his men to do quickly what they saw him do. All the men cut branches and followed Abimelek. They piled them against the stronghold and set it on fire. So all the people in the Tower of Shechem — about a thousand men and women — also died.`,
      `Abimelek then attacked Thebez and besieged it. Inside the city was a strong tower. All the citizens fled into it. While he was approaching the entrance of the tower to set it on fire, a woman dropped an upper millstone on his head and cracked his skull. Quickly he called to his armor-bearer: draw your sword and run me through, so that they can't say a woman killed me. His servant ran him through, and he died. When the Israelites saw that Abimelek was dead, they went home.`,
      `Thus God repaid the wickedness that Abimelek had done to his father by murdering his seventy brothers. God also made the people of Shechem pay for all their wickedness. The curse of Jotham came on them.`
