      `Jephthah the Gileadite was a mighty warrior. His father was Gilead; his mother was a prostitute. Gilead's wife also bore him sons, and when they had grown up, they drove Jephthah away. You are not going to get any inheritance in our family, they said, because you are the son of another woman.`,
      `The Ammonites made war on Israel. The elders of Gilead went to get Jephthah from the land of Tob. They said: come, be our commander, so we can fight the Ammonites. Jephthah said: didn't you hate me and drive me from my father's house? Why do you come to me now, when you are in trouble? The elders of Gilead said: nevertheless, we are turning to you now. Come with us to fight the Ammonites, and you will be our head over all who live in Gilead.`,
      `Jephthah sent messengers to the Ammonite king asking what quarrel he had with Israel. The king claimed Israel had taken the land when they came out of Egypt. Jephthah's reply was detailed — recounting the journey from Egypt, how Israel had not taken Moab or Ammon but had taken the land of the Amorites only after the Amorite king had refused peaceful passage. The Ammonite king paid no attention.`
