      `Ahab had seventy sons in Samaria. Jehu sent letters to their guardians: choose the best and most worthy of your master's sons and set him on his father's throne. Then fight for your master's house. They were terrified and sent word: we are your servants and will do whatever you tell us. Jehu sent a second letter: if you are on my side and will obey me, take the heads of your master's sons and come to me in Jezreel by this time tomorrow. The seventy princes were killed and their heads sent to Jehu in two baskets. He had them piled in two heaps at the city gate.`,
      `Jehu also killed all of Ahab's chief men, his close friends, and his priests — leaving him no survivor. He then met forty-two relatives of Ahaziah of Judah on the road and killed them too. He found Jehonadab son of Rekab, who was against Baal worship, and took him up into his chariot: come with me and see my zeal for the LORD. He called all the people together and said: Ahab served Baal a little; Jehu will serve him much more. He assembled all the prophets of Baal, all his servants, and all his priests. The temple of Baal was filled from one end to the other. When the burnt offering was finished, Jehu and the guards and officers killed them all. They demolished the sacred stone of Baal and demolished the temple. It became a latrine, as it still is today.`,
      `Yet Jehu was not careful to keep the law of the LORD with all his heart. He did not turn away from the sins of Jeroboam — the golden calves at Bethel and Dan.`
